<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n17022a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n17" href="#n17022a">N17 (VI.B.9)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n17all.htm#n17022a"> 22(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dormition <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n17022a"><li>FW 561.28 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n17022a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n17022a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n17022a">MS BL 47485-8</ms> </li><li>JJA 60:285 <a name="sd2y" href="../../ff/fdra/sda.htm#sd2y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd2.htm#n17022a">Draft: III&sect;4.2</a>+ </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The death or dormition (&lsquo;falling asleep&rsquo;) of Mary, the <i>Theotokos</i> or Mother of God. The term expresses the belief that the Virgin died without suffering, in a state of spiritual peace. This belief does not rest on any scriptural basis, but is affirmed by Orthodox Christian Holy Tradition. It is testified to in some old Apocryphal writings, but neither the Orthodox Church nor other Christians regard these as possessing scriptural authority. </mm> </dd></dl>
